    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect message size handling in WLS VNF/PNF procPhyMessages functions\n\n### Summary\nThe `procPhyMessages()` functions in both WLS VNF and PNF implementations were incorrectly modifying message sizes by adding header lengths when the extracted size already included the full message length (header + payload). This caused incorrect message processing and potential buffer overreads.\n\nThe issue occurred because:\n1. Message length was extracted from NFAPI header bytes 4-7 which contains total message length including headers\n2. Functions incorrectly added `NFAPI_NR_P5_HEADER_LENGTH` to all messages unconditionally  \n3. For P7 messages, an additional `NFAPI_NR_P7_HEADER_LENGTH` was added\n4. This resulted in handlers receiving inflated message sizes\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/oai_integration/wls_integration/wls_vnf.c`: Removed incorrect header length additions in `procPhyMessages()` function\n- `nfapi/oai_integration/wls_integration/wls_pnf.c`: Removed incorrect header length additions in `procPhyMessages()` function\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Run OAI VNF/PNF with WLS integration enabled\n2. Send NAS messages through the FAPI interface\n3. Observe incorrect message processing due to inflated message sizes\n4. Check for potential buffer overreads when processing short messages\n5. Compare behavior with socket implementation which works correctly\n\nThe fix ensures message sizes extracted from the NFAPI header are passed directly to handler functions without modification, matching the correct behavior of the socket implementation.\n"
}